      {
        "id": 4224308,
        "name": "Adam Frisch",
        "username": "Adam_Frisch",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/adam_frisch/{size}/3312_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-12-16T03:22:50.697Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Apologize if you already know this, but mercaptans often exhibit brimstone/sulphur notes and are often referred to as reductive. But they can take other forms too. They are often a byproduct of a ferment lacking in oxygen or nutrients - ie when yeast is stressed. Most of the time mercaptans go away with time and air, but sometimes they\u2019ve bound and remain in wine forever. If that\u2019s the case, it can be treated with copper sulfate, but is a pretty toxic and invasive process.</p>",
        "post_number": 2,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 5,
        "updated_at": "2023-12-16T03:25:40.747Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
        "reply_to_post_number": null,
