      {
        "id": 4224311,
        "name": "John Morris",
        "username": "John_Morris",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/john_morris/{size}/840_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-12-16T03:24:53.022Z",
        "cooked": "<p>It\u2019s very hard to know the chemistry behind someone\u2019s perception unless you\u2019re (a) tasting at the same time and (b) know something about wine chemistry.</p>\n<p>As I recall, there are lots of different kinds of mercaptins. Some give you a small like road tar. There are also other sulfur-based elements that might give a smoky BBQ element. And the grenache grape can yield some very earthy elements that I can imagine resembling some of the flavors in BBQ sauce.</p>",
        "post_number": 3,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 5,
        "updated_at": "2023-12-16T03:24:53.022Z",
        "reply_count": 1,
